      },
      "text": "Erysipelas\nDiagnosis usually clinical but blood cultures may be useful in severe cases or for patients with underlying comorbidities like diabetes\nUsually treated with IV antibiotics (ceftriaxone, cefazolin) but if no systemic symptoms then oral amoxicillin\nDescribed as “warm, tender, erythematous rash with raised, well-demarcated borders” and a good tell is if the external ear is involved (no dermis level to the external ear so makes it much less likely to be deeper infection like \ncellulitis)\nErysipelas",
      "textBlocks": [
        {
          "textBlockId": "Internal_Medicine_Shelf_Fast_Facts_s0003_b9d7bc22_text01",
          "text": "Erysipelas",
