      },
      "text": "Acute Nitrofurantoin-Induced Pulmonary Injury\nPresentation:\nNew-onset shortness of breath, fevers, dry cough, bilateral mid and lower lung opacities\nBasilar crackles, erythematous maculopapular rash, unilateral pleural effusion\nLeukocytosis and eosinophilia\nUsually symptoms start 3-9 days after medication initiation\nNot to be confused with:\nDrug-induced acute interstitial nephritis (AIN) → also causes fevers and eosinophilia, but will have nausea and vomiting as well as abnormal \ncreatinine\n, not pulmonary symptoms",
      "textBlocks": [
        {
          "textBlockId": "Internal_Medicine_Shelf_Fast_Facts_s0005_b9d7bc22_text01",
